<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF107-974-406  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 974 406.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Communications News  Dec 1989 v26 n12 p26(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>FBI stays secure, manages growth; 10Mb/s LAN thwarts unauthorizedtampering. (the US Federal Bureau of Investigation's fiber-opticLAN from 10Net Communications)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Stephenson, Peter.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The US Federal Bureau of Investigation (FBI) manages the flow ofinformation on a large network comprised of a broadband backbonewhich supports 300 field offices on a wide-area network, 1,200workstations and bridges to an IBM mainframe.andP;  In order tomaintain security, the FBI uses a fiber-optic local area network(LAN) from the 10Net Communications division of DigitalCommunications Associates.andP;  The FBI's network containsapproximately 40 secure fiber LAN clusters tied to a broadbandbackbone in the J. Edgar Hoover Building in Washington, DC.andP;  Awide-area network then connects 58 field divisions to a remote IBMmainframe or to FBI headquarters.andP;  Dave Evans, chief of theOperations Management Section of the FBI's Technical Services Div,installed WordPerfect Corp's WordPerfect Office as a workgroupshell.andP;  Evans plans eventually to move from DOS to OS/2.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   10net Communications (products).andO;Topic:     Local Area NetworksUnited States. Federal Bureau of InvestigationWide Area NetworksApplicationsFiber opticsLaw EnforcementNational GovernmentGovernment AgencyBackbone Networks.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>